def longest_palindrome(s: str) -> str:
    if not s or len(s) == 0:
        return ""

    def expand_around_center(left: int, right: int) -> str:
        while left >= 0 and right < len(s) and s[left] == s[right]:
            left -= 1
            right += 1
        return s[left + 1:right]

    longest = ""
    for i in range(len(s)):
        # Odd length palindromes (single character center)
        palindrome1 = expand_around_center(i, i)
        # Even length palindromes (two character center)
        palindrome2 = expand_around_center(i, i + 1)

        longest = max(longest, palindrome1, palindrome2, key=len)

    return longest  Time Complexity: $O(n^2)$. Expanding around its center takes $O(n)$ time, and we do this for each of the $2n - 1$ centers (each character and between each character).Space Complexity: $O(1)$ auxiliary space, as we are only storing indices/pointers, not creating new data structures (excluding the final substring returned).

def add_item(item, item_list=[]):
    item_list.append(item)
    return item_list  The Issues:

Mutable Default Argument: The default argument item_list=[] is evaluated only once when the function is defined, not each time the function is called. If you call this function multiple times without providing a list, it will keep appending to the exact same list in memory.
The Fix:  def add_item(item, item_list=None):
    if item_list is None:
        item_list = []
    item_list.append(item)
    return item_list

Base URL: /api/v1

1. Books Resource

GET /books (List books)

Response 200: [{"id": 1, "title": "1984", "author": "Orwell", "status": "available"}]

POST /books (Add a book)

Request: {"title": "Dune", "author": "Herbert", "isbn": "12345"}

Response 201: {"id": 2, "message": "Book created"}

GET /books/{id} (Get specific book)

Response 200: {"id": 1, "title": "1984", ...}

PUT /books/{id} (Update book details)

Request: {"title": "1984 - Revised"}

Response 200: {"message": "Book updated"}

DELETE /books/{id} (Remove book)

Response 204: (No Content)

2. Loans (Checkout) Resource

POST /loans (Checkout a book)

Request: {"user_id": 42, "book_id": 1}

Response 201: {"loan_id": 101, "due_date": "2026-06-26"}

Standard Error Handling

400 Bad Request: Invalid JSON payload (e.g., missing title).

404 Not Found: Trying to GET/PUT/DELETE a book_id that does not exist.

409 Conflict: Trying to checkout a book where status is "checked_out".

500 Internal Server Error: Database connection failure.

Error Format: {"error": {"code": 404, "message": "Book not found"}}
